author: reichwec

description.text:
The Duetwifi controller has an integrated webserver that supports an IP webcam.
I had an old S4 lying around that couldn't be used anymore as a phone but still had wifi.
I installed this Webcam app and that works fine!
So this is a first idea for a S4 mount to be connected on one of the 2020-beams of my FT5
Added a 45° version. Adjustment should be easier.

Modifications
After a while the previous design showed cracks as the S4 was a bit too heavy.
Redesigned both connections. Principle remains the same. Increased the size of the balls from 15 to 20mm = 77% more surface and thus more friction. Changed the connector to a separate and thicker piece (lock) with 2 bolts.
Lock has to be printed twice.
This one is ok for me now.

I printed all the pieces in PETG with 20% infill with a 0,6mm nozzle :

  • the holder standing up (no support needed) : 0,4mm layers
  • both ball joints on their flat surface : 0,32mm layers
  • the connection bar flat on the bed with support : 0,32mm layers
  • locks : 0,32mm layers

Other hardware :

  • 2 M3x14 to fix the holder on the small ball joint
  • 4 M3x20 for the connection bar
  • 12 M3 washers
  • 6 M3 nylock nuts
  • 2 M5 bolts and nut for the connection with the 2020-beam

Important remarks
The S4 becomes quite hot when in use as webcam unless you take some measures that can help avoiding overtemperatures :

  • remove backpanel (do not remove battery : held in place by the holder)
  • select option in the webcam app to continue in background and switch the screen off (you don't need to see on the screen what is happening or do you ? ;) )
  • I will test if installing a small fan would be an option

An IP webcam should have a fixed IP address. For those who don't know the howto in Android :

  • Connect to the wifi network you want to connect to
  • go into wifi settings and do a long press on the wifi the phone is connected with
  • choose second option : "modify network"
  • select show advanced options
  • change IP-settings from 'DHCP' to 'Static'
  • enter IP address and gateway;
Designed to automatically fit the plastic insert. I left too many parameters so you can customize it whatever way you want. Low poly, smooth, twisted... just open the customizer already.

remixed_from.title: modified lower bracket for microphone holder

description.text:
Fits for example an SM58 microphone and similar models, and has a 3/8" inside thread for mounting it to a microphone stand. Requires an M6x25 internal hex screw with corresponding nut (see https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2518438).

In contrast to the original thing (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:333971), this one doesn't require a nut at the bottom to mount to the stand, but has the thread readily included. Also, I heavily rounded the edges and completely redesigned the upper part holding the mic for a nice look, maximum adjustability and stable grip.

All parts seem to be very stable and durable with only 20% infill, but I didn't test them in prolonged use yet. I printed the clamp with supports and the other parts without supports and had very good results. See the Cura screenshot for my recommended printing orientations. This works best for me, but also my print bed adhesion is extremely strong, so a different orientation for the clamp might work better for different printers.

Update Sept., 21st:
The hex inset of the knob was a little too large, so it didn't fit all screw heads. I slightly reduced the sizes. Sorry for the inconvenience!

Update Sept., 22nd:
I added a slightly reinforced version (mic_clamp4.stl), in case you don't trust the stability or want a tighter grip on the microphone. It simply has .5 mm thicker walls around the microphone.

title: E3D V6 cold end blower fan adapter

description.text:
I wanted to be sure that there is enough cooling for the cold end of my V6. This led me to design an adapter for the stock blue fan shroud that can take a 40mm GDSTime blower fan (Search: GDStime 4020 blower fan).

EDIT: Added cable mount for Wanhao i3. I use it as the anchor point of my wiring loom seeing as I've done away with the drag chain.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:

If you enclose the printer regularly to print ABS you would likely print this in PETG or ABS.

The design

The design is centered around the stock E3D fan shroud and I consider it an adapter. This thing bolts directly onto the original shroud. The fan must be glued in place and mounting the adapter can be a tad difficult (more on this later).

Mounting the adapter

The part can be printed without support. After printing, screw the E3D screws a short way into the blue shroud (see picture).

Put the adapter 45 degrees out of phase on the blue shroud. You might need to use some (not excessive) force to do this (see picture).

Now twist the adapter into place and tighten the screws.

Screws in shroud 45 degrees out of phase Twist and lock Fan mount

Now you can glue in the fan. I used hot melt glue. Note: If you plan to enclose the printer hot melt glue does not work well. Use a temperature resistant glue.

Why glue? Because it is just so easy and it seals the adapter-fan interface.

description.text: One of my friends has just started working as tech support for the local university's library. I mentioned to her I should get her a rubber duck to help with troubleshooting (sometimes voicing the problem out loud helps find solutions - a tried and tested method used by other IT professionals) but she said she only wanted one if it was Harry Potter related. After a fruitless internet search I decided to make my own.

Printer:

Spacial One

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

15%

Notes:

Rotated 250ish degrees and then made flat using repetier so that the front geometry would be preserved and the support material on the back. See pic for help.

Support material removed with long nose pliers and a craft knife and the reart blasted with a heat gun for a bit to try and knock off some of the rough edges. If I had more time I would have gone for the sanding/filler/paint route but was a bit rushed.

Quick and dirty mashup in blender using cerebus333's sorting hat and the flat bottomed remix of Willie's original rubber Duck by deckerino. Pushed through netfabb to make sure it is watertight.

I was designing for looks not printability but I recon it can be tweaked without too much fuss

Mathstick was my second year at university project. It is currently displayed at London South Bank University Enterprise Centre.

There are 3 sets of 10 inter-connectable laser cut shapes (different colour for each denomination), I call them "sticks" (1s; 10s; 100s, but there is no limit really you can cut as many as you like and as far into 0000s as you want go, as space on the face permits). They can all interconnect to create number bonds and to be used to subtract, multiply and divide, or used to construct shapes with movable parts to boost kid's imagination when they are bore of maths.

My Pop-up-Shop project mood board I designed this toy not only for my university project, but to help my 4 year old daughter learn basic maths. I hope this project will keep helping other kids to develop understanding of number correlation and develop love for maths.

Mathstick can be used to assist teachers during the lesson as another visual/tactile aid for better comprehension of number correlation. This project can also be implemented in secondary schools as a way of learning CAD software and laser cutting in DT classes. The final products can then be passed on to younger grades for use. title: Solidoodle Workbench upgrade and replacement parts

description.text:
UPDATE: I have uploaded the custom firmware for the MKS v1.5 board with support for the LCD12864 full graphic smart controller.
I have also uploaded the parts in STEP format for anyone who wishes to modify them in a CAD program.

I was given a Solidoodle Workbench and liked the large print area it had, however the original design had some serious flaws, so I set about improving upon the original design.

The redesigned parts and assembly gives the Solidoodle Workbench a larger print volume, a quick change system for any J head, E3D V6 style hot end, and uses linear bearings on the X and Y axis.
The maximum usable print area is now X=360, Y=320, Z=300, However the practical print area may be a bit smaller.
I have redesigned the centre carriage with only 1 extruder to gain extra print area.
Any J head, E3D V6 or similar extruder will fit and the entire extruder can be swapped out with just 2 bolts.
I have not included the bed leveling system that the originally came with the printer.
I have reused parts where I can however the X axis is completely new, only the 10mm rods are reused. The extruder filament idler pulley and spring arm have also been reused.

I have borrowed some design elements and some common parts like switches and GT2 pulleys from the excellent Solidoodle 4 CoreXY rebuild by Elenhinan, however all of the the printable parts have been designed from scratch using Solidworks.
I have included the original files so you can modify them if required.
I have also included a zip file with the parts in STEP format so most common CAD program can open them.

The smaller holes in centre of the X, Y and centre carriages are oil holes to enable lubrication of the bearings in situ.
The bearings should just snap in, but they might be too tight or too loose depending on your print settings. They can be glued in with some silicone if required.

I have changed the motherboard to a MKS Base V1.5 and have added a solid state relay to handle the power for the heated bed.
I am also using a 12864 LCD Display (RepRap Discount Full Graphics Smart Controller)
I am using the latest version of Marlin 1.1.x
The default axis steps per unit in the configuration.h file is below:

{ 79.8, 61.538, 800, 100 } // MXL (2.03mm)belt // x=20 tooth, y=25 tooth,

(These settings work for me as the default Y axis belt is MXL and the new X axis belt is GT2, they may require some tweaking on your own machine if you use different size pulleys or screw rod)

I have had my machine up and running for about 6 months now and it produces great prints. I print mostly in ABS and would recommend enclosing the printer to keep the heat in. If the heated bed cannot heat fast enough the firmware can throw an error, (I had to adjust this in Configuration_adv.h (( #define WATCH_BED_TEMP_PERIOD 480 // Seconds)) to allow the bed to heat up slower)
I would recommend a default printing speed of about 30mm/s as printing any faster can produce unwanted vibrations that affect the print.

The MKS Base V1.5 has proven to be a good board, however I cannot recommend using the TFT32 touchscreen with it as the touchscreen firmware is closed source and buggy, and does not run correctly with the latest version of Marlin. I had to change to the 12864 LCD Display which so far has run flawlessly.

If I built a printer from scratch I would build a Core XY style printer, but these parts and modifications can turn an old Solidoodle Workbench into a great printer with a huge print area

Parts required:

1x GT2 20 tooth idler pulley (with bearings and 3mm shaft holes)
1x GT2 20 tooth pulley with 5mm shaft hole to fit stepper
1x 2m roll GT2 belt
1x Nema 17 42mm stepper (for X axis)
1x Nema 17 30mm stepper (for extruder, but can take up to 42mm)
8x LM10UU linear bearings
5x SS-5GL microswitches (the smaller style of microswitch)
1x 12V Blower fan for filament cooling
1x J Head, E3D v6 style extruder and cooling fan
Various M3 socket head bolts of 10mm to 40mm length
M3 Nylock nuts and normal nuts

Print in ABS for better strength.
Print with 4 layers on all walls for strength.
Resize parts approx 1.5% larger in your slicer program to allow for ABS shrinkage.
Bearings are snap fit but might require trimming or gluing in place.
Print carriages on their side for max strength.

End stop screw holes are designed for a M3 screw to be screwed straight in, but can be tapped for a better fit

comments.text:
The printer is going great so far. The only issue I've had was with the touchscreen control panel not communicating correctly with the MKS driver board. I've since changed the control panel to the generic LCD12864 full graphic control panel and have had no problems since. The touchscreen interface is loaded with closed source firmware which contains a bug that affects communication to the MKS v1.5 board.
Mechanically, the printer works fine so long as the print speed is not too high or you may get harmonic distortions in the lower levels of the print. I have set my print speed to 30mm/s max and I have had no issues so far. I would like to upgrade the aluminium cantilever base for the bed at some stage, as it is a bit too flimsy for my liking and I suspect that much of the vibration is due to the bed base.
I print everything in ABS plastic and the boxed in design keeps the heat in quite well. One thing to note is to increase the "bed temp increase watch time" in the firmware, as the bed takes a long time to heat up to 100 deg C and the firmware can throw an error if it takes too long. ( It took me hours to figure that out after it happened to me! )
I hope your upgrade goes well, and please post some pictures when it is finished.
Best of luck

description.text: This is for home rolled cables using DE-9 connector - 9 Pin D-Sub, serial, whatever you want to call it. 15 Pin (VGA) should work as well.

This is an alternate version to my other plug enclosure. I thought not needing to fiddle with screws would work better.
  • Print on 3D printer - I used ABS on a Makerbot
  • Roll the cable
  • Epoxy the shell together.
  • Enjoy plug'n'lock Nerdvana
    • The retaining clips are easy to bend, so you can open the connection. If you prefer to have non locking plugs, just use two of the inner shell for an easy push together, pull apart homemade cable. Have not tested how weather tight they are, yet. May need some kind of foam/rubber O ring to properly seal it. But in the meantime, they make a great connector for your projects and they look great when printed raftless! STL and Sketchup files included Earlier version has 4-40 screws holding them together. If there is interest in the screw together version vs. the glue together version I will clean them up and post them as well.

This is an upgraded filament guide for TEVO Titan extruder. I am not sure whether this fits original e3d Titan.

This solves problems with extruding flexible filament.

What is different:

  1. The original guide has a 5mm diameter conical entrance for the filament, which is some 7mm deep and then meets your PTF bowden. This is a perfect place for your filament to curl up and get stuck. My upgraded version is designed so that your bowden gets all the way through the guide and meets drive nut and guide pulley. As soon as the filament leaves the drive nut, it is trapped in a tight bowden tube, which is perfectly smooth all the way to the hotend.

  2. The filament guide in my Titan extruder was originally not in a perfect line with the guide pulley. To solve this, I made the new one slightly off-set. You can see the difference in the photo (the photo is showing a prototype which was misaligned slightly too much).

Notes:

  1. The hole in the model is 3mm wide and needs to be drilled to fit your bowdens diameter. I recommend to try smaller drill diameters and make the hole a tight fit, 4,1mm was perfect for me.

  2. After getting the bowden through, trim it as seen in the photo.

  3. For easy installation, load the bowden with both the guide and the "one-way lock nut (or what you call the part)" into the extruder body from a side, while the transparent extruder part is still off.

  4. The spring that pushes the guide pulley likes to shoot out while the extruder body is open, so get it out at the begining of the installation and put it back right before you screw the transparent part back on.

  5. Reloading a filament gets a little bit more difficult as the entrance is now much smaller than before, but it was not a big issue for me.

Please, let me know how it works for you, this is my first upload and any feedback will encourage me to make more useful things.

The cheap moulded plastic food can closures are made to such tight cost limits they inevitably fracture and tear apart especially if put in the fridge a lot, and washed in very hot water. Friends with a small dog that only needed a 1/2-can of food at a meal went through a few and asked if I could come up with a better one that could take a lot of use. This design is as basic as it gets & was my 1st tinkercad effort, but it does the job pretty well.

The stl is of the original which I printed in PLA (all I had to hand). So it had to be a little bit loose to snap over the metal roll-over rim on the can without breaking. Still worked fine though and if it rattling around is a bother, you can paint the inside with some epoxy or latex adhesive. That isn't OK for long-term food storage, but a day or two wouldn't present any appreciable risk of contamination. Of course, don't put PLA ones in the dishwasher! Unless you like modern art! Apparently my friend forgot PLA's glass temp of 55°C is lower than the 70°C dishwasher... So the next batch were done with my nice new roll of Rigid.Ink orange PETG.

To print in PETG (as my more recent ones have been) there are a couple of mods to make in the slicer. First, scale down to 99% - as PETG is a bit springy a tighter fit works fine. I tried one at 98% and it worked but took a lot of effort to press onto the can. Second, use a higher temp than usual - detail is less important than a smooth upper surface (the lower/inside surface when in use) - I go from my regular 230°C to 235. Finally set to give at least 0.4mm thick top and bottom layers. Infill is barely used so anything over 20% will work just fine unless you really care about a glass-smooth surface only your half-used tin of dogfood will ever see.
I'd always recommend PETG for this just because you can get that tighter fit without it exploding to pieces. Plus, in translucent orange, they're the best looking half-used-dog-food-tin covers around! :)

description.text: Hocus Pocus! You present your audience with six colored blocks, each one with a hole through its face. Your audience inspects the blocks as well as the box you will place them in and the pin you will pierce them with. A volunteer selects two of the six blocks. After placing all six blocks into the box, you pierce the box and all the blocks with a pin. Waving your hand over the box, you say a magic word. Turning the box upside down, the lid falls off and out drops the two chosen blocks! But wait the pin is still running through the box with the remaining blocks still pinned in place! See the demo video http://youtu.be/pmZhGH7pSUo Print this magic trick along with Thing 24719, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:24719 and put on an impromptu magic show! You'll be sure to amaze your friends and family.

Print either the "small" or "large" version of the trick. I recommend using the small version as the smaller blocks are less likely to tip over as you load them into the box. While there's nothing wrong with them tipping over, it is annoying and makes it look like you are fumbling or doing something tricky. On the other hand, if you want such an effect -- then use the large version! The large version uses six 20x20mm blocks while the small version uses six 20x14mm blocks. Not surprisingly, it will take you less time to print the smaller version. Small Version
  • Print pin.stl (same file works for either the small or large version).
  • Print six copies of small-block.stl. It looks best if you print each one a different color.
  • Print the box top and bottom: use either small-box.stl or the individual small-lid.stl and small-bottom.stl files. If you have problems with the print curling at the edges, then you may be better off printing the two pieces separately as that will have them closer to the center of your build platform.
  • You can use the magic-blocks.scad file to tweak any of the parts to your liking.
    • Large Version
  • Print pin.stl.
  • Print six copies of larger-block.stl. The trick looks best if you print each one a different color.
  • Print the box top and bottom: use either large-box.stl or the individual large-lid.stl and large-bottom.stl files. If you have problems with the print curling at the edges, then you may be better off printing the two pieces separately as that will have them closer to the center of your build platform.
  • You can use the magic-blocks.scad file to tweak any of the parts to your liking.
    • Performing the Trick
    To perform the trick,
  • Start with the blocks in the box with the pin running through them. Show the audience how the pin traps the blocks in place, preventing their removal.
  • Remove the pin and dump the blocks out. Allow the audience to inspect the blocks, box and pin.
  • Choose a volunteer from the audience to select two of the six blocks.
  • Using the lid to obscure the audience's view, return all six of the blocks to the box. However, place the two selected blocks in at 90 degrees from the other blocks:
    • | | |===| | |
    | | |===| | |
    ^^^ Two selected blocks
    ^^^ ^^^ Remaining 4 blocks
  • Close the box with the lid.
  • Pierce the blocks with the pin,
    • | | |===| | |
    ----------------o Pin
    | | |===| | |
  • Show the audience that all the blocks, including the chosen ones, are still in the box by letting them see the blocks through the peep holes in the box's lid and bottom.
  • Turn the box upside down but holding the lid in place.
  • Release the lid, allowing it and the two selected blocks to magically drop out of the box.
  • Show that the other blocks remain pinned! Jiggle the box a little if you need to prevent the audience from seeing the large gap left behind by the two selected blocks. Point being to not have them realize that those two blocks were put in sideways.
  • Take a bow or begin another trick such as Thing 24719, the magic coin piercing trick which you can also print!

This is a small tab that attaches to the Nerf Stryfe's jam door, made to prevent darts from feeding too far upwards along the mag, which would result in jams.

The design is at its first iteration, but could benefit from a few minor improvements with additional features, which I may eventually get to later.

Currently, the only reliable way to attach this is to drill holes and use screws. I attempted to use superglue but the plastic used on the jam door itself is not very cooperative, so I had to resort to screws.

I strongly recommend making rotations before printing by aligning any of the flat surfaces with the print bed. I prefer having it laid out flat, but stacking it upwards works too.

Not battle tested, but has passed basic firing tests with a few common dart types.

title: UARM Universal Adapter for Universal holder

description.text:
The UARM Swift Pro, Stepper motor driven robotic arm, comes with a Universal Holder (and a gripper). The part described above is a universal adapter for the universal holder.
It can be used as the base of a semicircular platform to mount several types of tools.
Each tool can be accessed simply by rotating the wrist.

The type of holder that you attach to the this Universal adapter for the holder will depend on what type of tool(s) that your mounting. I'm looking at mounting a small drill for drilling holes in circuit boards and a camera mount for a DinoCam digital "microscope".

These files include the Adapter for the universal gripper, the DinoCam Holder and the USB drill sleeve adapter. The USB drill can be powered and controlled through the side port on the UARM PRO (by changing or adapting a plug instead of the USB).
